# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: well-known-uri
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] In computing, **content negotiation** refers to mechanisms defined as a part of HTTP that make it possible to serve different versions of a document (or more generally, representations of a resource) at the same URI, so that user agents can specify which version fits their capabilities the best.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] One classical use of this mechanism is to serve an image in GIF or PNG format, so that a browser that cannot display PNG images (e.g.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] MS Internet Explorer 4) will be served the GIF version.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] A resource may be available in several different representations; for example, it might be available in different languages or different media types.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] One way of selecting the most appropriate choice is to give the user an index page and let them select the most appropriate choice; however it is often possible to automate the choice based on some selection criteria.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] HTTP provides for several different content negotiation mechanisms including: server-driven (or proactive), agent-driven (or reactive), transparent, and/or hybrid combinations thereof.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] Server-driven or proactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms on the server which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on user agent-provided acceptance criteria.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the user agent informs the server what media types or other aspects of content presentation it understands with ratings of how well it understands them.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] More precisely, the user agent provides HTTP headers that lists acceptable aspects of the resource and quality factors for them.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] The server is then able to supply the version of the resource that best fits the user agent's needs.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] Where the 'q' - quality - factor for German is higher than that for English.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] Multiple HTTP headers are often supplied together for content format or, specifically media type, language and a few other aspects of a resource.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] In addition to the commonly used `Accept` header for Media Type, the `Accept-Language` header for language negotiation, RFC 7231 also describes `Accept-Charset` & `Accept-Encodings` for character encodings and content codings (compression) respectively.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] Neither RFC 7231 nor the more recent related specifications such as *Content Negotiation by Profile* specify how to resolve trade-offs in cases where different headers specify conflicting requirements, such as, in the above example, choosing between an HTML page in English and a GIF image in German.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] Agent-driven or reactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms in the user-agent which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on a server provided list of representations and metadata about them.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the server informs the user-agent which representations it has available as well as any metadata it has about each representation (e.g., content-type, quality, language, etc.).
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] The user-agent then resubmits the request to a specific URL for the chosen representation.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] This can be automatically chosen by the user-agent or the user-agent can present the user with the choices and the user can directly choose such.
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] More precisely, the server responds with either 300 Multiple Choices or 406 Not Acceptable (when server-driven, user-agent acceptance criteria are provided but the server cannot automatically make a selection).
[src:well-known-uri/content-negotiation] Unfortunately HTTP leaves the format of the list of representations and metadata along with selection mechanisms unspecified.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:well-known-uri/http] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:well-known-uri/http] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:well-known-uri/http] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:well-known-uri/http] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:well-known-uri/http] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:well-known-uri/http] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:well-known-uri/http] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:well-known-uri/http] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:well-known-uri/http] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:well-known-uri/http] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:well-known-uri/http] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:well-known-uri/http] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:well-known-uri/http] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:well-known-uri/http] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:well-known-uri/http] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:well-known-uri/http] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:well-known-uri/http] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:well-known-uri/http] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:well-known-uri/http] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:well-known-uri/http] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:well-known-uri/http] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:well-known-uri/http] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:well-known-uri/http] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:well-known-uri/http] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:well-known-uri/http] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:well-known-uri/http] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:well-known-uri/http] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:well-known-uri/http] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:well-known-uri/http] include the representation data in the body.
[src:well-known-uri/http] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:well-known-uri/http] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:well-known-uri/http] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:well-known-uri/http] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:well-known-uri/http] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:well-known-uri/http] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:well-known-uri/http] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:well-known-uri/http] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The following is a request with no body.
[src:well-known-uri/http] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:well-known-uri/http] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:well-known-uri/http] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:well-known-uri/http] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:well-known-uri/http] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:well-known-uri/http] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:well-known-uri/http] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:well-known-uri/http] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:well-known-uri/http] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:well-known-uri/http] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:well-known-uri/http] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:well-known-uri/http] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:well-known-uri/http] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:well-known-uri/http] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:well-known-uri/http] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:well-known-uri/http] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:well-known-uri/http] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:well-known-uri/http] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:well-known-uri/http] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The **Robots Exclusion Protocol** (often referred to by the filename used to implement it, **robots.txt**) is a standard used by websites to indicate to visiting web crawlers and other web robots which portions of the website they are allowed to visit.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The standard, developed in 1994, relies on voluntary compliance.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Malicious bots can use the file as a directory of which pages to visit, though standards bodies discourage countering this with security through obscurity.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The standard was used in the 1990s to mitigate server overload.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] In the 2020s, websites began denying bots that collect information for generative artificial intelligence.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The "robots.txt" file can be used in conjunction with sitemaps, another robot inclusion standard for websites.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The standard was proposed by Martijn Koster, when working for Nexor in February 1994 on the *www-talk* mailing list, the main communication channel for WWW-related activities at the time.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Charles Stross claims to have provoked Koster to suggest robots.txt, after he wrote a badly behaved web crawler that inadvertently caused a denial-of-service attack on Koster's server.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The standard, initially RobotsNotWanted.txt, allowed web developers to specify which bots should not access their website or which pages bots should not access.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The internet was small enough in 1994 to maintain a complete list of all bots; server overload was a primary concern.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] By June 1994 it had become a *de facto* standard; most complied, including those operated by search engines such as WebCrawler, Lycos, and AltaVista.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] On July 1, 2019, Google announced the proposal of the Robots Exclusion Protocol as an official standard under Internet Engineering Task Force.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] A proposed standard was published in September 2022 as RFC 9309.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] A site owner wishing to give instructions to web robots places a text file called robots.txt in the root of the web site hierarchy (e.g. https://www.example.com/robots.txt).
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] This text file contains the instructions in a specific format (see examples below).
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Robots that choose to follow the instructions try to fetch this file and read the instructions before fetching any other file from the website.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] If this file does not exist, web robots assume that the website owner does not wish to place any limitations on crawling the entire site.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] A robots.txt file contains instructions for bots indicating which web pages they can and cannot access.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Robots.txt files are particularly important for web crawlers from search engines such as Google.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] A robots.txt file on a website will function as a request that specified robots ignore specified files or directories when crawling a site.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] This might be, for example, out of a preference for privacy from search engine results, or the belief that the content of the selected directories might be misleading or irrelevant to the categorization of the site as a whole, or out of a desire that an application only operates on certain data.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Links to pages listed in robots.txt can still appear in search results if they are linked to from a page that is crawled.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] For websites with multiple subdomains, each subdomain must have its own robots.txt file.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] If example.com had a robots.txt file but foo.example.com did not, the rules that would apply for example.com would not apply to foo.example.com.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] In addition, each URI scheme and port needs its own robots.txt file; http://example.com/robots.txt does not apply to pages under http://example.com:8080/ or https://example.com/.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The robots.txt protocol is widely complied with by bot operators.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The robots.txt played a role in the 1999 legal case of *eBay v.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Bidder's Edge*, where eBay attempted to block a bot that did not comply with robots.txt, and in May 2000 a court ordered the company operating the bot to stop crawling eBay's servers using any automatic means, by legal injunction on the basis of trespassing.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Bidder's Edge appealed the ruling, but agreed in March 2001 to drop the appeal, pay an undisclosed amount to eBay, and stop accessing eBay's auction information.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Harding*, a company was sued for accessing protected web pages archived via The Wayback Machine, despite robots.txt rules that prevented those pages from being archived.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] A Pennsylvania court ruled "in this situation, the robots.txt file qualifies as a technological measure" under the DMCA.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Due to a malfunction at Internet Archive, Harding could temporarily access these pages from the archive and thus the court found "the Harding firm did not circumvent the protective measure".
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Holdings, Inc.* the Associated Press sued Meltwater for copyright infringement and misappropriation over copying of AP news items.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Meltwater claimed that they did not require a license and that it was fair use, because the content was freely available and not protected by robots.txt.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The court decided in March 2013 that "Meltwater’s copying is not protected by the fair use doctrine", mentioning among several factors that "failure […] to employ the robots.txt protocol did not give Meltwater […] license to copy and publish AP content".
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Some web archiving projects ignore robots.txt.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Archive Team uses the file to discover more links, such as sitemaps.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Co-founder Jason Scott said that "unchecked, and left alone, the robots.txt file ensures no mirroring or reference for items that may have general use and meaning beyond the website's context." In 2017, the Internet Archive announced that it would stop complying with robots.txt directives.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] According to *Digital Trends*, this followed widespread use of robots.txt to remove historical sites from search engine results, and contrasted with the nonprofit's aim to archive "snapshots" of the internet as it previously existed.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Starting in the 2020s, web operators began using robots.txt to deny access to bots collecting training data for generative AI.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] In 2023, Originality.AI found that 306 of the thousand most-visited websites blocked OpenAI's GPTBot in their robots.txt file and 85 blocked Google's Google-Extended.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Many robots.txt files named GPTBot as the only bot explicitly disallowed on all pages.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Denying access to GPTBot was common among news websites such as the BBC and *The New York Times*.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] In 2023, blog host Medium announced it would deny access to all artificial intelligence web crawlers as "AI companies have leached value from writers in order to spam Internet readers".
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] GPTBot complies with the robots.txt standard and advises web operators about how to disallow it, but *The Verge*'s David Pierce said this only began after "training the underlying models that made it so powerful".
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Also, some bots are used both for search engines and artificial intelligence, and it may be impossible to block only one of these options.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] *404 Media* reported that companies like Anthropic and Perplexity.ai circumvented robots.txt by renaming or spinning up new scrapers to replace the ones that appeared on popular blocklists.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] In 2025, the nonprofit RSL Collective announced the launch of the Really Simple Licensing (RSL) open content licensing standard, allowing web publishers to set terms for AI bots in their robots.txt files.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Participating companies at launch included Medium, Reddit, and Yahoo.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Despite the use of the terms *allow* and *disallow*, the protocol is purely advisory and relies on the compliance of the web robot; it cannot enforce any of what is stated in the file.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Malicious web robots are unlikely to honor robots.txt; some may even use the robots.txt as a guide to find disallowed links and go straight to them.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] While this is sometimes claimed to be a security risk, this sort of *security through obscurity* is discouraged by standards bodies.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Many robots also pass a special user-agent to the web server when fetching content.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] A web administrator could also configure the server to automatically return failure (or pass alternative content) when it detects a connection using one of the robots.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Some sites, such as Google, host a `humans.txt` file that displays information meant for humans to read.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Some sites such as GitHub redirect humans.txt to an *About* page.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Previously, Google had a joke file hosted at `/killer-robots.txt` instructing the Terminator not to kill the company founders Larry Page and Sergey Brin.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] This example tells all robots that they can visit all files because the wildcard `*` stands for all robots and the `Disallow` directive has no value, meaning no pages are disallowed.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] This example has the same effect, allowing all files rather than prohibiting none.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The same result can be accomplished with an empty or missing robots.txt file.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] All other files in the specified directory will be processed.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] It is also possible to list multiple robots with their own rules.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The actual robot string is defined by the crawler.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] A few robot operators, such as Google, support several user-agent strings that allow the operator to deny access to a subset of their services by using specific user-agent strings.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The directive `Disallow: /something/` blocks all files and subdirectories starting with `/something/`.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] It would not prevent the crawling of `/something/foo/else`, as that would not match the pattern.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The wildcard `*` allows greater flexibility but may not be recognized by all crawlers, although it is part of the Robots Exclusion Protocol (RFC).
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] A wildcard at the end of a rule in effect does nothing, as that is the standard behaviour.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The crawl-delay value is supported by some crawlers to throttle their visits to the host.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Since this value is not part of the standard, its interpretation is dependent on the crawler reading it.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] It is used when the multiple burst of visits from bots is slowing down the host.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Yandex interprets the value as the number of seconds to wait between subsequent visits.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Bing defines crawl-delay as the size of a time window (from 1 to 30 seconds) during which BingBot will access a web site only once.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Google ignores this directive, but provides an interface in its search console for webmasters, to control the Googlebot's subsequent visits.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The *Robot Exclusion Standard* does not mention the "*" character in the `Disallow:` statement.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Cloudflare introduced `Content-Signal` as a directive to suggest acceptable crawler behavior by type, `ai-train`, `ai-input`, and `search` with values of `yes` or `no` for each.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] In addition to root-level robots.txt files, robots exclusion directives can be applied at a more granular level through the use of Robots meta tags and X-Robots-Tag HTTP headers.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The robots meta tag cannot be used for non-HTML files such as images, text files, or PDF documents.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] On the other hand, the X-Robots-Tag can be added to non-HTML files by using .htaccess and httpd.conf files.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The X-Robots-Tag is only effective after the page has been requested and the server responds, and the robots meta tag is only effective after the page has loaded, whereas robots.txt is effective before the page is requested.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] Thus if a page is excluded by a robots.txt file, any robots meta tags or X-Robots-Tag headers are effectively ignored because the robot will not see them in the first place.
[src:well-known-uri/robots-txt] The Robots Exclusion Protocol requires crawlers to parse at least 500 kibibytes (512000 bytes) of robots.txt files, which Google maintains as a 500 kibibyte file size restriction for robots.txt files.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In particular, the resource need not be retrievable via the Internet, or any computer network.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] URIs which provide a means of locating and retrieving information resources on a network (like the Internet, an Intranet or a computer file system) are Uniform Resource Locators (URLs).
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Other URIs provide only a unique name, without a means of locating or retrieving the resource or information about it; these are Uniform Resource Names (URNs).
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The web technologies that use URIs are not limited to web browsers.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In 1990, Tim Berners-Lee's proposals for hypertext implicitly introduced the idea of a URL as a short string representing a resource that is the target of a hyperlink.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] At the time, people referred to it as a "hypertext name" or "document name".
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Over the next three and a half years, as the World Wide Web's core technologies of HTML, HTTP, and web browsers developed, a need to distinguish a string that provided an address for a resource from a string that merely named a resource emerged.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Although not yet formally defined, the term *Uniform Resource Locator* came to represent the former, and the more contentious *Uniform Resource Name* came to represent the latter.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In July 1992 Berners-Lee's report on the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) "UDI (Universal Document Identifiers) BOF" mentions URLs (as Uniform Resource Locators), URNs (originally, as Unique Resource Numbers), and the need to charter a new working group.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In November 1992 the IETF "URI Working Group" met for the first time.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] During the debate over defining URLs and URNs, it became evident that the concepts embodied by the two terms were merely aspects of the fundamental, overarching, notion of resource *identification*.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In June 1994, the IETF published RFC 1630, Berners-Lee's first *Request for Comments* that acknowledged the existence of URLs and URNs.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Most importantly, it defined a formal syntax for *Universal Resource Identifiers* (i.e.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] URL-like strings whose precise syntaxes and semantics depended on their schemes).
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] It also attempted to summarize the syntaxes of URL schemes in use at the time.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] It acknowledged—*but did not standardize*—the existence of relative URLs and fragment identifiers.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In December 1994, RFC 1738 formally defined relative and absolute URLs, refined the general URL syntax, defined how to resolve relative URLs to absolute form, and better enumerated the URL schemes then in use.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The agreed definition and syntax of URNs had to wait until the publication of IETF RFC 2141 in May 1997.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The publication of IETF RFC 2396 in August 1998 saw the URI syntax become a separate specification and most of the parts of RFCs 1630 and 1738 relating to URIs and URLs in general were revised and expanded by the IETF.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In December 1999, RFC 2732 provided a minor update to RFC 2396, allowing URIs to accommodate IPv6 addresses.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A number of shortcomings discovered in the two specifications led to a community effort, coordinated by RFC 2396 co-author Roy Fielding, that culminated in the publication of IETF RFC 3986 in January 2005.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] While obsoleting the prior standard, it did not render the details of existing URL schemes obsolete; RFC 1738 continues to govern such schemes except where otherwise superseded.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] IETF RFC 2616 for example, refines the `http` scheme.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Simultaneously, the IETF published the content of RFC 3986 as the full standard STD 66, reflecting the establishment of the URI generic syntax as an official Internet protocol.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In 2001, the World Wide Web Consortium's (W3C) Technical Architecture Group (TAG) published a guide to best practices and canonical URIs for publishing multiple versions of a given resource.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] For example, content might differ by language or by size to adjust for capacity or settings of the device used to access that content.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In August 2002, IETF RFC 3305 pointed out that the term "URL" had, despite widespread public use, faded into near obsolescence, and serves only as a reminder that some URIs act as addresses by having schemes implying network accessibility, regardless of any such actual use.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] As URI-based standards such as Resource Description Framework make evident, resource identification need not suggest the retrieval of resource representations over the Internet, nor need they imply network-based resources at all.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The Semantic Web uses the HTTP URI scheme to identify both documents and concepts for practical uses, a distinction which has caused confusion as to how to distinguish the two.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The *TAG* published an e-mail in 2005 with a solution of the problem, which became known as the *httpRange-14 resolution*.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The W3C subsequently published an Interest Group Note titled "Cool URIs for the Semantic Web", which explained the use of content negotiation and the HTTP 303 response code for redirections in more detail.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A Uniform Resource Name (URN) is a URI that identifies a resource by name in a particular namespace.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A URN may be used to talk about a resource without implying its location or how to access it.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] For example, in the International Standard Book Number (ISBN) system, *ISBN 0-486-27557-4* identifies a specific edition of the William Shakespeare play *Romeo and Juliet*.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] However, it gives no information as to where to find a copy of that book.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A Uniform Resource Locator (URL) is a URI that specifies the means of acting upon or obtaining the representation of a resource, i.e. specifying both its primary access mechanism and network location.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] For example, the URL `http://example.org/wiki/Main_Page` refers to a resource identified as `/wiki/Main_Page`, whose representation is obtainable via the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (*http:*) from a network host whose domain name is `example.org`.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] (In this case, HTTP usually implies it to be in the form of HTML and related code.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A URN is analogous to a person's name, while a URL is analogous to their street address.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In other words, a URN identifies an item and a URL provides a method for finding it.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Technical publications, especially standards produced by the IETF and by the W3C, normally reflect a view outlined in a W3C Recommendation of 30 July 2001, which acknowledges the precedence of the term URI rather than endorsing any formal subdivision into URL and URN.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] As such, a URL is simply a URI that happens to point to a resource over a network.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] However, in non-technical contexts and in software for the World Wide Web, the term "URL" remains widely used.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Additionally, the term "web address" (which has no formal definition) often occurs in non-technical publications as a synonym for a URI that uses the *http* or *https* schemes.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Such assumptions can lead to confusion, for example, in the case of XML namespaces that have a visual similarity to resolvable URIs.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Specifications produced by the WHATWG prefer *URL* over *URI*, and so newer HTML5 APIs use *URL* over *URI*.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] While most URI schemes were originally designed to be used with a particular protocol, and often have the same name, they are semantically different from protocols.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] For example, the scheme *http* is generally used for interacting with web resources using HTTP, but the scheme *file* has no protocol.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A URI has a scheme that refers to a specification for assigning identifiers within that scheme.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] As such, the URI syntax is a federated and extensible naming system wherein each scheme's specification may further restrict the syntax and semantics of identifiers using that scheme.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The URI generic syntax is a superset of the syntax of all URI schemes.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] It was first defined in RFC 2396, published in August 1998, and finalized in RFC 3986, published in January 2005.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A percent-encoding of an identifying data octet is a sequence of three characters, consisting of the character `%` followed by the two hexadecimal digits representing that octet's numeric value.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A component is *undefined* if it has an associated delimiter and the delimiter does not appear in the URI; the scheme and path components are always defined.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A component is *empty* if it has no characters; the scheme component is always non-empty.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Additionally, the generic reserved character `:` may be used in the userinfo, path, query and fragment, the generic reserved characters `@` and `/` may be used in the path, query and fragment, and the generic reserved character `?` may be used in the query and fragment.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The following displays example URIs and their component parts.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] DOIs (digital object identifiers) fit within the Handle System and fit within the URI system, as facilitated by appropriate syntax.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A *URI reference* is either a URI or a *relative reference* when it does not begin with a scheme component followed by a colon (`:`).
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A path segment that contains a colon character (e.g., `foo:bar`) cannot be used as the first path segment of a relative reference if its path component does not begin with a slash (`/`), as it would be mistaken for a scheme component.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Such a path segment must be preceded by a dot path segment (e.g., `./foo:bar`).
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] URL munging is a technique by which a command is appended to a URL, usually at the end, after a "?" token.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] It is commonly used in WebDAV as a mechanism of adding functionality to HTTP.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In a versioning system, for example, to add a "checkout" command to a URL, it is written as `http://editing.com/resource/file.php?command=checkout`.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] It has the advantage of both being easy for CGI parsers and also acts as an intermediary between HTTP and underlying resource, in this case.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] In XML, a namespace is an abstract domain to which a collection of element and attribute names can be assigned.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] The namespace name is a character string which must adhere to the generic URI syntax.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] However, the name is generally not considered to be a URI, because the URI specification bases the decision not only on lexical components, but also on their intended use.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A namespace name does not necessarily imply any of the semantics of URI schemes; for example, a namespace name beginning with *http:* may have no connotation to the use of the HTTP.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] Originally, the namespace name could match the syntax of any non-empty URI reference, but the use of relative URI references was deprecated by the W3C.
[src:well-known-uri/uniform-resource-identifier] A separate W3C specification for namespaces in XML 1.1 permits Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI) references to serve as the basis for namespace names in addition to URI references.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] WebFinger is specified as the discovery protocol for OpenID Connect, which is a protocol that allows one to more easily log in to various sites on the Internet.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] The WebFinger protocol is used by federated software, such as GNU social (via its use in OStatus), Diaspora, or Mastodon, to discover users on federated nodes and pods, as well as the remoteStorage protocol.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] The WebFinger protocol does not specify the usage of "template" within the "links" section.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] That is an extension made by the former oStatus protocol that the Fediverse inherited from.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] The reasoning for expanding upon this later was justified by wanting to use a different key for a value that isn't an URL but a pattern to create one.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] As a historical note, the name "WebFinger" is derived from the old ARPANET Finger protocol, but it is a very different protocol designed for HTTP.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] The protocol payload is represented in JSON format with a MIME-Type of `application/jrd+json`.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] The WebFinger specification consists of a specified URI format and a minimal ontology which requires JSON resources served from that URI to declare their own additional ontologies.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] The application can then parse the JSON, using the `"rel"` properties to find appropriate uses for each URI.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] For example, links with `"rel"` `http://webfinger.net/rel/profile-page` can be used for populating the user's homepage field, and those with `"rel"` `http://webfinger.net/rel/avatar` could be used as a profile picture.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] Fediverse-based social networking software like Mastodon, PeerTube, and Misskey can look up the server name of a specific username by sending a request to the WebFinger endpoint of the domain within their username (the part after the 2nd `@`-symbol).
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] This allows any entity with their own DNS domain name to have a consistent (set of) Fediverse username(s), without having to run the software on their own domain.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] For individuals, this feature allows the user to keep a consistent username (and its associated social capital) even if they switch instances by serving a JSON file with the appropriate `/.well-known/webfinger?resource=...` path on their webserver.
[src:well-known-uri/webfinger] WebFinger aware platforms and clients first send an HTTP GET request to `https://mastodon.social/.well-known/webfinger?resource=acct%3AMastodon%40mastodon.social`.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] A **well-known URI** is a Uniform Resource Identifier for URL path prefixes that start with `/.well-known/`.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] They are implemented in webservers so that requests to the servers for **well-known services** or information are available at URL consistent **well-known locations** across servers.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] Well-known URIs are Uniform Resource Identifiers defined by the IETF in RFC 8615.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] They are URL path prefixes that start with `/.well-known/`.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] This implementation is in response to the common expectation for web-based protocols to require certain services or information be available at URLs consistent across servers, regardless of the way URL paths are organized on a particular host.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] The URIs are implemented in webservers so that requests to the servers for well-known services or information are available at URLs consistently in well-known locations across servers.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] The IETF has defined a simple way for web servers to hold metadata that any user agent (e.g., web browser) can request.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] The metadata is useful for various tasks, including directing a web user to use a mobile app instead of the website or indicating the different ways that the site can be secured.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] The well-known locations are used by web servers to share metadata with user agents; sometimes these are files and sometimes these are requests for information from the web server software itself.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] The way to declare the different metadata requests that can be provided is standardized by the IETF so that other developers know how to find and use this information.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] The path well-known URI begins with the characters `/.well-known/`, and whose scheme is "HTTP", "HTTPS", or another scheme that has explicitly been specified to use well-known URIs.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] As an example, if an application hosts the service "example", the corresponding well-known URIs on `https://www.example.com/` would start with `https://www.example.com/.well-known/example`.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] Information shared by a web site as a well-known service is expected to meet a specific standard.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] Specifications that need to define a resource for such site-wide metadata can register their use with the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) to avoid collisions and minimize impingement upon sites' URI space.
[src:well-known-uri/well-known-uri] The list below describes known standards for .well-known services that a web server can implement.
